{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639002","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639002"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:02:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:02:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17756"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17756"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.67,0.19,0.11,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10470"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72238"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10470"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17756"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57708"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24439"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24443"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72238"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine check-up. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She does not consume alcohol and has no history of liver disease. As part of her check-up, liver function tests are performed. One of these tests analyses a cytosolic enzyme primarily found in the liver, which is released when hepatocytes are damaged.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following liver function tests is this enzyme?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alanine aminotransferase (ALT)","Alkaline phosphatase (ALP)","Aspartate aminotransferase (AST)","Gamma-glutamyl transferase (GGT)","Bilirubin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlanine aminotransferase (ALT)\u003C/strong\u003E is a cytosolic enzyme primarily found in the liver. It is released into the bloodstream when hepatocytes are damaged, making it a specific marker for liver injury. ALT is more specific to the liver compared to \u003Cstrong\u003Easpartate aminotransferase (AST)\u003C/strong\u003E, which is also present in other tissues such as the heart and muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlkaline phosphatase (ALP)\u003C/strong\u003E is an enzyme found in the liver, bones, and other tissues. It is often elevated in conditions affecting the bile ducts or bone disorders, rather than direct hepatocyte damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGamma-glutamyl transferase (GGT)\u003C/strong\u003E is an enzyme found in the liver and is often used to assess liver function, particularly in the context of alcohol use or bile duct obstruction. However, it is not as specific for hepatocyte damage as ALT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBilirubin\u003C/strong\u003E is a product of red blood cell breakdown and is processed by the liver. Elevated bilirubin levels can indicate liver dysfunction, but it is not an enzyme released by damaged hepatocytes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Alanine aminotransferase (ALT) is a cytosolic enzyme primarily found in the liver and is released into the bloodstream when hepatocytes are damaged.","ALT is more specific to liver injury compared to aspartate aminotransferase (AST), which is also found in other tissues such as the heart and muscles.","Liver function tests help in assessing liver health and diagnosing liver diseases."],"references":["Kasarala G, Tillmann HL. Standard liver tests. Clin Liver Dis (Hoboken). 2016 Jul 26;8(1):13-18. doi: 10.1002/cld.562. PMID: 31041056; PMCID: PMC6490189.","Hall P, Cash J. What is the real function of the liver \u0027function\u0027 tests? Ulster Med J. 2012 Jan;81(1):30-6. PMID: 23536736; PMCID: PMC3609680.","Thapa BR, Walia A. Liver function tests and their interpretation. Indian J Pediatr. 2007 Jul;74(7):663-71. doi: 10.1007/s12098-007-0118-7. PMID: 17699976.","Lala V, Zubair M, Minter DA. Liver Function Tests. 2023 Jul 30. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29494096."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57708"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17756"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57708","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57708"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T05:49:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T05:50:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10470"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72238"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{